        "title": "How to inject Session/User object after bootstrapping?",
        "body": "<p>There are examples where different kinds of objects are getting injected into a presenter, but I can't find an explanation how this can be done.<\/p>\n\n<p>In the <a href=\"http://dev.arcbees.com/gwtp/get-started/Bootstrap-Code.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bootstrap-Code<\/a> example they are injecting e.g. a <code>SecurityDelegate<\/code> object. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also in the <a href=\"http://dev.arcbees.com/gwtp/core/security/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gatekeeper<\/a> example I see things being injected, e.g. <code>MyGatekeeper<\/code>, but how is this done?<\/p>\n\n<p>What I want is to first check if the user is logged in and then create a <code>CurrentSession<\/code> object or something like this. But how can I pass/inject this object around?<\/p>\n\n<p>At the moment I am initializing a singleton object <code>CurrentUser<\/code> which is kind of ugly imho. I would like to get the GWTP support running, but how?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Take this example of the <code>CurrentSession<\/code> being injected into the gatekeeper:<\/p>\n\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>@DefaultGatekeeper\npublic class LoggedInGatekeeper implements Gatekeeper {\n    private final CurrentSession currentSession;\n\n    @Inject\n    LoggedInGatekeeper(CurrentSession currentSession) {\n        this.currentSession = currentSession;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public boolean canReveal() {\n        return currentSession.isLoggedIn();\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>How do I inject <code>CurrentSession<\/code> here? <\/p>\n",
